{{Short description|Deliberate destruction of the home}} {{multiple image | perrow = 2 | align=right | direction= horizontal | total_width=370 | header = Notable examples of domicide | image1 = Damage in Gaza Strip during the October 2023 - 29.jpg | caption1 = [[Israeli bombing of the Gaza Strip|Bombing of the Gaza Strip]] | image2 = Tokyo-kushu-hikaku.jpg | caption2 = [[Bombing of Tokyo]] | image3 = Fotothek df ps 0000010 Blick vom Rathausturm.jpg | caption3 = [[Bombing of Dresden]] | image4 = Płonąca oblężona Warszawa.jpg | caption4 = [[Bombing of Warsaw in World War II|Bombing of Warsaw]] }} '''Domicide''' (from [[Latin]] ''domus'', meaning home or abode, and ''caedo'', meaning deliberate killing, though used here metaphorically), is the destruction of housing for corporate, political, strategic or bureaucratic reasoning.<ref name=":12">{{Cite web |title=Domicide {{!}} McGill-Queen’s University Press |url=https://www.mqup.ca/domicide-products-9780773522589.php |access-date=2024-08-29 |website=www.mqup.ca}}</ref> It can also encompass the widespread destruction of a living environment, forcing the incumbent humans to move elsewhere.<ref>{{cite web |last=Sullivan |first=Becky |date=9 February 2024 |title=What is 'domicide,' and why has war in Gaza brought new attention to the term? |url=https://www.npr.org/2024/02/09/1229625376/domicide-israel-gaza-palestinians |accessdate=21 May 2024 |website=[[National Public Radio]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Porteous |first=Douglas |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mOwb3IXYfoEC&q=topocide&pg=PA12 |title=Domicide: The Global Destruction Of Home |author2=Sandra E. Smith |publisher=McGill-Queen's Press - MQUP |year=2001 |isbn=9780773569614 |page=12}}</ref> In a [[Right to housing|human rights]] context, domicide is the deliberate and systematic destruction of housing and basic infrastructure, making an area uninhabitable.<ref name=":02">{{Cite news |title=Amid Israeli Destruction in Gaza, a New Crime Against Humanity Emerges: Domicide |url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/2024-01-04/ty-article-magazine/.highlight/amid-israeli-destruction-in-gaza-a-new-crime-against-humanity-emerges-domicide/0000018c-d585-d751-ad8d-ffa5965e0000 |access-date=2024-01-05 |work=Haaretz |language=en}}</ref> The concept of domicide originated in the 1970s, but only assumed its present meaning in 2022, after a report by the UN Special Rapporteur on the Right to Adequate Housing, Balakrishnan Rajagopal<ref name=":02" /><ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-10-28 |title=Report of the Special Rapporteur on adequate housing as a component of the right to an adequate standard of living, and on the right to non-discrimination in this context, Balakrishnan Rajagopal (A/77/190) [EN/AR/RU/ZH] - World {{!}} ReliefWeb |url=https://reliefweb.int/report/world/report-special-rapporteur-adequate-housing-component-right-adequate-standard-living-and-right-non-discrimination-context-balakrishnan-rajagopal-a77190-enarruzh |access-date=2024-01-05 |website=reliefweb.int |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=October 28, 2022 |title="Domicide" must be recognised as an international crime: UN expert |url=https://www.ohchr.org/en/press-releases/2022/10/domicide-must-be-recognised-international-crime-un-expert |website=Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights}}</ref>
Rajagopal has argued that [[international law]] should be amended to consider domicide to be a [[war crime]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Rajagopal |first=Balakrishnan |date=2024-01-29 |title=Opinion {{!}} Domicide: The Mass Destruction of Homes Should Be a Crime Against Humanity |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2024/01/29/opinion/destruction-of-homes-crime-domicide.html |access-date=2024-01-29 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>
== Examples == Notable historical examples of domicide include: the [[Bombing of Tokyo]], which was the most destructive and deadly non-nuclear bombing in human history,<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Long |first=Tony |date=9 March 2011 |title=March 9, 1945: Burning the Heart Out of the Enemy |url=https://www.wired.com/2011/03/0309incendiary-bombs-kill-100000-tokyo/ |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |quote=1945: In the single deadliest air raid of World War II, 330 American B-29s rain incendiary bombs on Tokyo, touching off a firestorm that kills upwards of 100,000 people, burns a quarter of the city to the ground, and leaves a million homeless.}}</ref> the bombing of [[Warsaw]] and [[Dresden]] and the destruction perpetrated by the [[Khmer Rouge]] in [[Cambodian Civil War#War crimes|Cambodia]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Collins |first=Andrew E |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BDfqfikFDmsC&q=topocide&pg=PA109 |title=Disaster and Development |publisher=Routledge |year=2009 |isbn=9780203879238 |page=109}}</ref>
The recent [[Israeli bombing of the Gaza Strip]] is considered to be the one of the most destructive campaigns in history.{{Citation needed|date=November 2024}} Balakrishnan Rajagopal, advisor to the United Nations on dams and Special Rapporteur on adequate housing has argued that Israel did domicide in the [[Gaza Strip]] during the [[Israel–Hamas war|Israel-Hamas war]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-03-05 |title=UN rights expert condemns ‘systematic’ war-time mass destruction of homes {{!}} UN News |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2024/03/1147272 |access-date=2024-08-29 |website=news.un.org |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Mr. Balakrishnan Rajagopal |url=https://www.ohchr.org/en/special-procedures/sr-housing/mr-balakrishnan-rajagopal |website=United Nations Human Rights}}</ref>
